def plot_classes(data_df, class_col="class"):
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,5))
    for cls in data_df[class_col].unique():
        temp = data_df[data_df[class_col] == cls]
        plt.scatter(temp.X1, temp.X2, label=cls)
    plt.xlabel("X1")
    plt.ylabel("X2")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
plot_classes(data, class_col="class")

a) Apply PCA to reduce the number of dimensions to one and visualize the instances on a scatter plot. Note that the scatter plot will show the observation number versus the observed value (as we have a single feature to represent the instance).¶

In [6]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

pca = PCA(n_components=None, random_state=3136)
scaler = MinMaxScaler()

X = data[["X1", "X2"]].values
X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
reduced_dim = pca.fit_transform(X)[:, 0]
print(pca.singular_values_)
data["pca_dim"] = reduced_dim

plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
for cls in data["class"].unique():
    temp = data[data["class"] == cls]
    plt.scatter(temp.index, temp.pca_dim, label=cls)
plt.xlabel("Index")
plt.ylabel("PCA C1")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

b) Apply MDS to reduce the number of dimensions to one and visualize the instances on a scatter plot as in part (a). Use at least two different similarity measure.¶

In [7]:
from sklearn.manifold import MDS
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import euclidean_distances, manhattan_distances, cosine_distances

X = data[["X1", "X2"]].values
X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
l2_dist_matrix = euclidean_distances(X)
l1_dist_matrix = manhattan_distances(X)
cos_dist_matrix = cosine_distances(X)

matrices = (l2_dist_matrix, l1_dist_matrix, cos_dist_matrix)
names = ("L2 Distance", "L1 Distance", "Cosine Distance")

for dist, name in zip(matrices, names):
    mds = MDS(n_components=1, dissimilarity="precomputed", random_state=3136)
    mds_dim = mds.fit_transform(dist)
    
    col_name =f"mds_dim_{name}"
    data[col_name] = mds_dim
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    for cls in data["class"].unique():
        temp = data[data["class"] == cls]
        plt.scatter(temp.index, temp[col_name], label=cls)
    plt.xlabel("Index")
    plt.ylabel("MDS C1")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title(name)
    plt.show()

c) On a 2D scatter plot, one can observe how two observations from two classes are different.¶

  1. What is your conclusion when you use PCA results in single dimension (your results from part a)?
  2. What is your conclusion when you use MDS results in single dimension (your results from part b)? Compare the results from different similarity measures used in part (b)
  3. Compare MDS results with PCA. What is your conclusion?

1)¶

When the initial values are plotted, circular pattern with different radius for each class is observed. Since PCA is used for linear relationships and the plot does not imply any linear relationship, it wouldn't expect PCA to work. When the first component is checked it appears this statetement is true.

In [8]:
print("PC1: ", pca.components_.T[0])

PC1:  [8.65976117e-04 9.99999625e-01]

Basically it selects centered X2 for the most of the first component and PCA seems to have not much usage in this. Classes can not be seperated even with two decision boundaries when the component is considered. So, PCA did not worked in this case.

2)¶

MDS with L2 norm basically tries to obtain the same space. In case of having two decision boundaries for the component, 4 blue observations are misclassified. For L1 norm things change. The misclassified point can be classified correctly by specifying an interval for class a. For cosine similarity the plot seems chaotic. Since cosine similarity considers the angles between observations, in terms of classification it makes everything much more complex.

3)¶

In this setting using MDS with L1 distance seems to be the most desirable dimensionality reduction method since it allows to construct an interval for red class perfectly while PCA would have 4 misclassified observations in case of having the best interval.

It appears matrix is not symmetric. So a symmetric matrix is obtained by taking average of upper and lower triangular part.

In [15]:
dist_matrix = tr_dist.drop(columns=["L PLAKA NO", "L ADI"]).values
lower_tri = np.tril(dist_matrix)
upper_tri = np.triu(dist_matrix)
symm_lower_tri = (lower_tri + upper_tri.T)/2
symm_dist_matrix = symm_lower_tri + symm_lower_tri.T
# Is matrix symmetric now?
(symm_dist_matrix==symm_dist_matrix.T).all()
Out[15]:
True

Also the overall look implies the shape of the country.

Task 3 – Dimensionality reduction for time series data¶

Read the data and visualize one instance (all axes) from each class and try to relate the shape (time series) you see with the gestures shown in Figure 1 (this is just for fun, sometimes it is good to start with data visualization to understand what is going on). A 3D scatter plot would be interesting. Note that this is an acceleration information. You can transform this information to a velocity vector by computing the cumulative sum of acceleration over time. A cumulative sum operation on the velocity values will transform the series to a position information.

In [18]:
def read_data(path):
    with open(path, "r") as file:
        lines = file.readlines()
    
    classes = [float(x.replace("  ", " ").split()[0]) for x in lines]
    lines = [list(map(float, x.replace("  ", " ").split()))[1:] for x in lines]
    return np.array(lines), classes

b)¶

As you may have noticed, the data is provided as a regular data matrix (i.e. each row represents an instance and columns represent the time index of the observations). Assume that X, Y and Z variables are concatenated to obtain a single time series in an unusual way as follows: concatenated series = [x1 x2 . xT y1 y2 . yT z1 z2 . zT ] In other words, the information from X, Y and Z axis are concatenated to obtain a single series of length 3T (each axis is represented by a time series of length T). Apply PCA to the time series from each class in the training data. You are expected to filter the data from each class and apply PCA to the representation. Work on the following questions based on your PCA application for the time series from each class. How much variability can be recovered by the first two components? Draw the each eigenvector (component) as a time series for each class. What do the eigenvectors imply in this setting? In total, you are expected to provide 8 plots. Each plot is expected to provide two time series (i.e. first eigenvector and the second eigenvector). Are there any interesting patterns/observations? If yes, provide your comments

I believe it makes more sense to work on position data. Therefore I will use it since the question does not specify.

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
for cls in np.unique(classes):
    idxs = (classes == cls)
    temp = combined[idxs]
    
    pca = PCA(n_components=None, random_state=3136)
    temp = scaler.fit_transform(temp)
    pca.fit(temp)
    print(f"Class: {int(cls)} Var Ratio explained : ", pca.explained_variance_ratio_[:2])
    eigen_vec = pca.components_[:2]
    
    ax = fig.add_subplot(2, 4, int(cls))
    ax.plot(list(range(eigen_vec.shape[1])), eigen_vec[0], label="PC1")
    ax.plot(list(range(eigen_vec.shape[1])), eigen_vec[1], label="PC2")
    ax.set_xlabel("Index")
    ax.set_ylabel("PCA_vals")
    ax.set_title(f"Class: {int(cls)}")
    ax.legend()

The components together explains at least %60 of the variance up to %84 percent. This ratio should be enough to make comments. The plot of the eigenvectors clearly includes three different patterns with jumps after every 315 observations. Which corresponds to axis changes in the representation.

The first PCA components show the directions that contains the most variance in the data and they are unit vectors. Therefore having a large absolute coefficient means that at that time there were more variability than the other times. Since if every gesture is done perfectly no variance should be presented in the direction of the movement we would expect variability in the axes does not have part in the gesture. However people start from different places in the movement direction or in the other direction which causes variability. Class 5 and 6 shows this in very clearly. The movement is in the Z axis and people start from different X and Y values that causes most variablity in PC1s but Z axis contributes much less. Also these straight gestures tend to have less variability through time in the movement axis, usually at the end while making tails of the gestures. However circular shapes have much more variablity in movement directions since circular shapes creates a lot of possible positions to follow.
